BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Let [`P(n)`] be the statement that [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}n + 3 \lt n + 7\text{.}`] We will prove that [`P(n)`] is true for all [`\renewcommand{\d}{\displaystyle}\newcommand{\N}{\mathbb N}n \in \N\text{.}`] First, note that the base case holds: [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}0+3 \lt 0+7\text{.}`] Now assume for induction that [`P(k)`] is true. That is, [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}k+3 \lt k+7\text{.}`] We must show that [`P(k+1)`] is true. Now since [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}k + 3 \lt k + 7\text{,}`] add 1 to both sides. This gives [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}k + 3 + 1 \lt k + 7 + 1\text{.}`] Regrouping [`\renewcommand{\v}{\vtx{above}{}}\newcommand{\lt}{<}(k+1) + 3 \lt (k+1) + 7\text{.}`] But this is simply [`P(k+1)\text{.}`] Thus by the principle of mathematical induction [`P(n)`] is true for all [`\renewcommand{\d}{\displaystyle}\newcommand{\N}{\mathbb N}n \in \N\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

